def luddy_block_generation(block_zize):
  idx = np.random.randint(low=0, high=1010)
  R = X_R[idx: idx+8, :]

  img_data = [X_R, X_G, X_B]
  n_times = [block_zize - 1 ,block_zize, block_zize]
  for n, data in zip(n_times, img_data):
    for i in range(n):
      idx = np.random.randint(low=0, high=1010)
      img_block = X_R[idx: idx+8, :]
      R = np.hstack((R, img_block))
  R = R.astype('float64')
  print("R shape : ", R.shape)
  return R
In [ ]:
def plot_eigen_matrix(R, n):
  R_mean = np.mean(R, axis=1).reshape((-1, 1))
  print("R mean shape :", R_mean.shape)
  # print(R_mean)

  # Subtract the mean vector of size 8  1 from all 6912 vectors.
  R -= R_mean
 
  # Calculate the covariance matrix, which will be an 8  8 matrix
  covMatrix = np.cov(R,bias=True)
  # print("The covariance matrix is :\n",covMatrix)
  plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
  plt.imshow(covMatrix)

  # Do eigendecomposition on the covariance matrix and extract 8 eigenvectors(V), each of which is with 8 dimensions.
  V, W = np.linalg.eigh(covMatrix)
  print("Eigen Vector shape:", V.shape)
  print("Eigen Matrix shape:", W.shape)
  print("Eigen Vector : \n", V)
  # Plot your W.
  # sns.heatmap(np.round(W.T, 1), annot=False)
  plt.imshow(W.T, cmap='Blues', interpolation='nearest')
  plt.title(f'Eigen Matrix for block size ' +str(n), size=20)
  plt.colorbar()
  plt.axis(False)
  plt.show()

# For easy comparison of plot without any print statements

def plot_eigen_decomposition(R, n):
  R_mean = np.mean(R, axis=1).reshape((-1, 1))

  # Subtract the mean vector of size 8  1 from all 6912 vectors.
  R -= R_mean

  # Calculate the covariance matrix, which will be an 8  8 matrix
  covMatrix = np.cov(R,bias=True)
  V, W = np.linalg.eigh(covMatrix)
  
  # Do eigendecomposition on the covariance matrix and extract 8 eigenvectors(V), each of which is with 8 dimensions.
  plt.imshow(W.T, cmap='Blues', interpolation='nearest')
  plt.title(f'Eigen Matrix for block size ' +str(n), size=20)
  plt.colorbar()
  plt.axis(False)
  plt.show()

Conclusion

  • From the above plots for block size 3 nd 30 , te row vector size was 6912 and 69120 respectively.
  • We can conclude that when we increase the number of samples that we input to our covariance matrix our covariance weights gets much better.
  • Comparing both the plots, the plot using 90 samples has captured higher variance than the plot using 9 samples.

Building the covariance matrix and the Eigen vectors and Eigen Matrix¶

https://learndataa.com/2020/09/15/data-preprocessing-whitening-or-sphering-in-python/

  • Zero-center data: $$ x_{\text {centered }}=x-x_{\text {mean }} $$

where,

x_centered: centered data for a feature
x: is individual data point for a feature
xmean: mean value for a feature

  • Covariance matrix: $$ \begin{gathered} x_{\text {variance }}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-x_{\text {mean }}\right)^{2}}{n} \\ \\ \text { covariance }=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-x_{\text {mean }}\right)\left(y_{i}-y_{\text {mean }}\right)}{n} \end{gathered} $$
$$ x_{\text {variance }}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-x_{\text {mean }}\right)^{2}}{n-1} $$$$ x_{\text {covariance }}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-x_{\text {mean }}\right)\left(y_{i}-y_{\text {mean }}\right)}{n-1} $$

where:

x_variance: is variance for a feature
x_covariance: is covariance between features x and y
xi and yi: is individual data point for feature x and y
x_mean and y_mean: mean value for features x and y
: indicates sum of values
n: is the number of observations for a feature


  • Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors: $$ A-\lambda I=0 $$ Equation 6: Substitute covariance matrix for 'A' and solve the simultaneous equations to calculate ' $\lambda$ ' i.e. Eigenvalues $$ A v=\lambda v $$ Equation 7 : Substitute the Eigenvalues ' $\lambda$ ' from above Equation# 6 along with the covariance matrix 'A' to calculate the Eigenvectors.
    where:

A: Covariance matrix of features
: is the matrix for Eigenvalues
I: is identity matrix
v: is the matrix for Eigenvectors

  • Whitening using PCA: $$ W_{P C A}=\Lambda^{\frac{-1}{2}} U^{T} X $$

where:

X: Feature data
: is the matrix for Eigenvalues (above is inverse square root)
UT: is transpose of matrix for Eigenvectors


  • Whitening using ZCA:
$$ W_{Z C A}=U \Lambda^{\frac{-1}{2}} U^{T} X $$

Equation 9: Whitening transformation using ZCA.

X: Feature data
: is the matrix for Eigenvalues (above is inverse square root)
UT: is transpose of matrix for Eigenvectors

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6574782/how-to-whiten-matrix-in-pca

In [ ]:
def pca_whitening(X_in):
  # zero centered data set. 
  X_in = X_in - np.mean(X_in, axis =1).reshape(-1,1)
  
  # Calculate the covariance matrix, which will be an 4  4 matrix
  covMatrix = np.cov(X_in,bias=True)
  print("The covariance matrix is :\n",covMatrix)

  # Do eigendecomposition on the covariance matrix and extract 8 eigenvectors(V), each of which is with 8 dimensions.
  d, V = np.linalg.eigh(covMatrix)
  print("\nEigen Vector shape:", d.shape)
  print("\nEigen Matrix shape:", V.shape)
  print("\nEigen Vector : \n", d)
  print("\nEigen Matrix : \n", V)

  epsilon = 1e-5
  # a fudge factor can be used so that eigenvectors associated with
  # small eigenvalues do not get overamplified.
  D = np.diag(1. / np.sqrt(d+epsilon))

  # whitening matrix
  W = np.dot(np.dot(V, D), V.T)

  # multiply by the whitening matrix
  X_white = np.dot(W, X)

  return X_white, W

Independent Component Analysis¶

At every iteration of the ICA algorithm, use these as your update rules:
$$ \begin{aligned} \Delta \boldsymbol{W} & \leftarrow\left(N \boldsymbol{I}-g(\boldsymbol{Y}) f(\boldsymbol{Y})^{\prime}\right) \boldsymbol{W} \\ \boldsymbol{W} & \leftarrow \boldsymbol{W}+\rho \Delta \boldsymbol{W} \\ \boldsymbol{Y} & \leftarrow \boldsymbol{W} \boldsymbol{Z} \end{aligned} $$

$\begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{W} &: \text { The ICA unmixing } \mathrm{mat} \\ \boldsymbol{Y} &: \text { The } 4 \times N \text { source mat } \\ Z &: \text { Whitened version of } \\ g(x) &: \tanh (x), \text { (works eleme } \\ f(x) &: x^{3}, \text { (works element-w } \\ \rho &: \text { learning rate } \\ N &: \text { number of samples } \end{aligned}$

In [ ]:
def Independent_Component_Analysis(Z, lr, N):
    delta_W= np.identity(4)
    W = np.identity(4)
    Y = np.dot(W,Z)
    I = np.identity(4)

    for i in range(0, 1000):
        delta_W = np.dot((N * I - np.dot(np.tanh(Y), np.power(Y, 3).T)), W)
        W = W + lr *delta_W
        Y = np.dot(W,Z)
    return Y, W

Signal to Noise Ratio(SNR)¶

$$ S N R=10 \log _{10}\left(\frac{\sum_{t}\{s(t)\}^{2}}{\sum_{t}\{s(t)-\hat{s}(t)\}^{2}}\right) $$
In [ ]:
S_abs = np.abs(S)
S_recov_abs = np.abs(S_recov)
In [ ]:
def snr_calculate(S, S_recov):
  return 10 *  (np.log10(np.sum(S ** 2)/ (np.sum((S-S_recov) **2 ))))
In [ ]:
print(f"The SNR of Ideal Mask is: {np.real(snr_calculate(S_abs, S_recov_abs))}")
